# Git Push Safety - MANDATORY

Before EVERY `git push` command, you MUST:

1. Run `git status` to check for uncommitted local changes
2. If there ARE uncommitted changes (modified/untracked files), STOP and warn the user
3. Ask the user whether those changes should be committed first
4. NEVER push if there are uncommitted local changes without explicit user approval

This prevents Vercel/CI rebuilds from deploying an incomplete state that is missing local work.

## Example workflow

```
# ALWAYS do this before pushing:
git status

# If output shows modified/untracked files:
# -> STOP, warn user, ask if they should be committed first
# -> Only push after user confirms the working tree state is acceptable

# If output shows "nothing to commit, working tree clean":
# -> Safe to push
```

## When committing specific files only

If you are staging only specific files (e.g. `git add file1 file2`), you MUST still check if there are OTHER uncommitted changes that might be important. If there are, warn the user that those files will NOT be included in the deployment.
